  <section toc="overview" name="Overview">
     <desc><p>
	After building the Micro-PET I noticed, that for further features, I would have to get larger than 
	a Euro-card. The challenge - for me at least - is that I use an older, private-use restricted
	version of Eagle that can only do Euro-card PCBs, but not larger.
	</p><p>
	So, the current version is based on multiple Euro-PCBs, but will eventually be combined into a
	single PCB.
	</p><p>
	The main development is happening on github (see link left in the menu).
	</p>
     </desc>
     <subsection toc="features" name="Features">
	<desc>
A number of features are planned, not all of them have been implemented at this time.

<ul>
  <li>Micro-PET as base</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Commodore 3032 / 4032 / 8032 / 8296 with options menu to select at boot</li>
    <ul>
        <li>Boot-menu to select different PET versions to run</li>
        <li>40 col character display</li>
        <li>80 col character display</li>
        <li>8296 memory map emulation</li>
        <li>IEEE488 interface (card edge)</li>
        <li>Tape connector (card edge)</li>
        <li>PET graphics keyboard, or alternatively a C64 keyboard</li>
    </ul>
    <li>Improved system design:</li>
    <ul>
        <li>512k video RAM, 512k fast RAM accessible using banks on the W65816 CPU</li>
        <li>boot from an SPI Flash ROM</li>
        <li>up to 12.5 MHz mode (via configuration register)</li>
        <li>VGA b/w video output</li>
        <li>Write protection for the PET ROMs once copied to RAM</li>
        <li>lower 32k RAM mappable from all of the 512k fast RAM</li>
    </ul>
    <li>Improved Video output:</li>
    <ul>
        <li>Hires graphics mode (using a configuration register)</li>
        <li>modifyable character set</li>
        <li>40/80 column display switchable</li>
        <li>25/50 rows display switch</li>
        <li>multiple video pages mappable to $8000 video mem address</li>
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <li>Extra features on top</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Colour-PET compatibility (as defined by Steve Gray's colour-PET project)</li>
    <li>Potentially Colour hires modes</li>
    <li>Simpler and more versatile system bus:</li>
    <ul>
      <li>CS/A bus (my standard)</li>
      <li>Some Apple-II bus compatibility</li>
      <li>RC2014 bus connectors</li>
    </ul>
    <li>Built-in disk drive simulator (e.g. nano488 or pico488)</li>
    <li>Built-in Userport extensions, like Joystick ports, or even WLAN modem support</li>
  </ul>
</ul>
	<p>
	As mentioned, the current design uses multiple PCBs, esp. the Ultra-CPU and the
	Ultra-Bus. The Ultra-CPU, Ultra-Bus and the existing CS/A PETIO board already
	make up a Colour-PET clone.
	</p>

